            [
                'id'           => 2,
                'title'        => 'Five Things I Wish I Knew Before Starting My Business',
                'slug'         => 'five-things-i-wish-i-knew-before-starting-my-business',
                'excerpt'      => 'The honest lessons Ruth wishes someone had told her before she launched My Perfect Stitch — practical wisdom for first-time entrepreneurs.',
                'body'         => '<p>When I left my government job to start My Perfect Stitch, I was confident. I had a product people wanted. I had savings. I had a plan — or at least, something I was calling a plan.</p><p>What I did not have was the hard-won knowledge that only comes from doing the thing. Here are five lessons I would go back and tell myself if I could.</p><h2>1. Your First Price Is Almost Always Too Low</h2><p>I underpriced my work for the first eighteen months. I was afraid that if I charged what the work was worth, clients would walk away. Most of them would not have. Price your work honestly from the beginning — it is far harder to raise prices later than to set them right from the start.</p><h2>2. Cash Flow Is Not the Same as Profit</h2><p>I had months where the business looked healthy on paper but I was scrambling to pay suppliers. Understanding the difference between revenue, profit, and cash in your account is not optional knowledge for a business owner. Learn it early.</p><h2>3. Your Network Is Your First Market</h2><p>Every significant early client I had came through a personal connection. Not advertising. Not a website. A conversation with someone who already trusted me. Invest in relationships before you need them.</p><h2>4. Saying No Is a Business Strategy</h2><p>In the early days I took almost every commission, even the ones that did not fit what I was trying to build. Each misfit project cost me more than it paid — in time, in energy, and in the direction of the brand. Learning to say no to the wrong work is how you make room for the right work.</p><h2>5. The Business Will Become What You Practice</h2><p>If you practice cutting corners, the business becomes one that cuts corners. If you practice quality — in the work, in the communication, in the relationships — the business becomes known for quality. Every small decision is practice. Choose carefully what you are rehearsing.</p>',
